int bufr_set_environment ( char *  default_bufrtables,
char *  bufrtables_dir 
)

set the environment vars needed to work properly with ECMWF bufrdc library

Parameters
default_bufrtablesdefaut bufr tables dir. ususally '/usr/local/lib/bufrtables/'
bufrtables_diralternative char with bufr tables dir

During decoding Bufr table path and the names are printed. If user doeas not want that, set: VARIABLE PRINT_TABLE_NAMES=false

During decoding code/flag tables could be read if code figure meaning is needed. If user want to use code and flag tables set: VARIABLE USE TABLE C=true

Then we set the proper environment here

328  if ( s->a->mask & DESCRIPTOR_VALUE_MISSING )
329  {
330  return 0;
331  }
332  if ( c->e.DD[0] == 0 )
333  {
334  sprintf ( c->e.DD, "%02d", s->ival );
335  }
336  if ( s->a1->desc.x == 8 && s->a1->desc.y == 53 )
337  {
338  s->more_days = s->isq_val;
339  }
340  s->day = s->ival;
341  s->mask |= SUBSET_MASK_HAVE_DAY;
342  break;
343 
344  case 4: // 0 04 004 . Hour
345  if ( s->a->mask & DESCRIPTOR_VALUE_MISSING )
346  {
347  return 0;
348  }
349  if ( c->e.HH[0] == 0 )
350  {
351  sprintf ( c->e.HH, "%02d", s->ival );
352  }
353  s->mask |= SUBSET_MASK_HAVE_HOUR;
354  break;
355 
356  case 5: // 0 04 005 . Minute
357  if ( s->a->mask & DESCRIPTOR_VALUE_MISSING )
358  {
359  return 0;
360  }
361  if ( c->e.mm[0] == 0 )
362  {
363  sprintf ( c->e.mm, "%02d", s->ival );
364  }
365  s->mask |= SUBSET_MASK_HAVE_MINUTE;
366  break;
367 
368  case 22: // 0 04 022 . Num month. Case of sec2 with normals
369  if ( s->a->mask & DESCRIPTOR_VALUE_MISSING )
370  {
371  return 0;
372  }
373  s->month = s->ival;
374  break;
375 
376  case 23: // 0 04 023 . Num days in month
377  if ( s->a->mask & DESCRIPTOR_VALUE_MISSING )
378  {
379  return 0;
380  }
381  if ( s->nday == 0 )
382  {
383  s->nday = s->ival;
384  }
385  break;
386 
387  case 51: // 0 04 051 . Principal time of daily reading of maximum
388  if ( s->a->mask & DESCRIPTOR_VALUE_MISSING )
389  {
390  return 0;
391  }
392  sprintf ( c->s4.GxGx, "%02d", s->ival );
393  s->mask |= CLIMAT_SEC4;
394  break;
395 
396  case 52: // 0 04 052 . Principal time of daily reading of minimum
397  if ( s->a->mask & DESCRIPTOR_VALUE_MISSING )
398  {
399  return 0;
400  }
401  sprintf ( c->s4.GnGn, "%02d", s->ival );
402  s->mask |= CLIMAT_SEC4;
403  break;
404 
405  case 53: // 0 04 053 . Number of days with precipitation equal to or more than 1 mm
406  if ( s->a->mask & DESCRIPTOR_VALUE_MISSING )
407  {
408  return 0;
409  }
410  if ( s->is_normal == 0 )
411  {
412  sprintf ( c->s1.nrnr, "%02d", s->ival );
413  s->mask |= CLIMAT_SEC1;
414  }
415  else
416  {
417  sprintf ( c->s2.nrnr, "%02d", s->ival );
418  s->mask |= CLIMAT_SEC2;
419  }
420  break;
421 
422 
423  case 74: // 0 04 074 . (UTC - LST)
424  if ( s->a->mask & DESCRIPTOR_VALUE_MISSING )
425  {
426  return 0;
427  }
428  s->dift = s->ival;
429  break;
430 
431 
432  default:
433  break;
434  }
435  return 0;
436 }

char* get_bufrfile_path ( char *  filename,
char *  err 
)

Get bufr file names to parse.

Parameters
filenamestring where the file is on output
errstring where to set the error if any

If success, it returns a pointer to filename. If there is no more files to parse, or error returns NULL.

This routine is also opens the file with file list and close it when no more file available in list

The content format in LISTOFFILES is compatible with 'ls -1'. Example assume we want to parse all *.bufr files in current directory, we can do

ls -1 *.bufr > list_file && bufr2synop -I list_file

Get the complete pathname of a table file needed by a bufr message.

Parameters
targetthe resulting name
typea char with type, i.e, 'B', 'C', or 'D'
bufrtables_dirstring with path to bufr file tables dir
ksec1array of integer processed prevoiously by ecmwf bufr library In ECMWF library the name of a table file is Kssswwwwwxxxxxyyyzzz.TXT , where
  • K - type of table, i.e, 'B', 'C', or 'D'
  • sss - Master table number (zero for WMO meteorological tables)
  • wwwww - Originating sub-centre
  • xxxxx - Originating centre
  • yyy - Version number of master table used
  • zzz - Version number of local table used

If standard WMO tables are used, the Originating centre xxxxx will be set to

int guess_gts_header ( struct gts_header *  h,
const char *  f 
)

Guess the WMO GTS header from filename.

Parameters
hpointer to a struct gts_header where to set the results
fpathname of bufrfile

It returns 1 if guessed, 0 otherwise

This routine assume the filename format of a bufr file is
  YYYYMMDDHHmmss_BULLNN_ICAO_YYGGgg_ORD.bufr
where
 YYYYMMDDHHmmss
is the timestamp (UTC) of the file in GTS (as example, in NOAA gateway)
BULLNN is the bulletin identifier in GTS. It is a six chars lenght in the form T1 T2 A1 A2 N1 N2
  For observations, T1 is 'I'
  Possible values of T2 for T1 = 'I' are
     O   Oceanographic/limnographic (water properties)
     P   Pictorial
     S   Surface/sea level
     T   Text (plain language information)
     U   Upper air
     X   Other data types
     Z   Mixed data types
  For T1T2 = 'IS' Then A1:
     IS A 01–29 Routinely scheduled observations for n/a 000/006
                distribution from automatic (fixed or mobile)
                land stations (e.g. 0000, 0100, … or 0220, 0240,
                0300, …, or 0715, 0745, ... UTC)
     IS A 30–59 N-minute observations from automatic (fixed n/a 000/007
                or mobile) land stations
     IS B   Radar reports (parts A and B) RADOB 006/003
     IS C 01–45 Climatic observations from land stations CLIMAT 000/020
     IS C 46–59 Climatic observations from marine stations CLIMAT SHIP 001/0202009 edition
                ATTACHmENT II-5 I
     IS D   Radiological observation RADREP 010/001
     IS E   Ozone measurement at surface n/a 008/000
     IS F   Source of atmospherics SFAZI, SFLOC, SFAZU 000/030
     IS I 01–45 Intermediate synoptic observations from fixed SYNOP (SIxx) 000/001
            land stations 000/051
     IS I 46–59 Intermediate synoptic observations from mobile SYNOP mOBIL 000/004
            land stations
     IS M 01–45 Main synoptic observations from fixed land SYNOP (SMxx) 000/002
            stations 000/052
     IS M 46–59 Main synoptic observations from mobile land SYNOP mOBIL 000/005
             stations
     IS N 01–45 Synoptic observations from fixed land stations SYNOP (SNxx) 000/000
            at non-standard time (i.e. 0100, 0200, 0400,   000/050
            0500, ... UTC)
     IS N 46–59 Synoptic observations from mobile land stations SYNOP mOBIL 000/003
            at non-standard time (i.e. 0100, 0200, 0400,
            0500, ... UTC)
     IS R   Hydrologic reports HYDRA 000/040
     IS S 01–19 Synoptic observations from marine stations SHIP 001/000
     IS S 20–39 One-hour observations from automatic marine n/a 001/006
           stations
     IS S 40–59 N-minute observations from automatic marine n/a 001/007
           stations
     IS T 01–19 Tide gauge observations n/a 001/030
     IS T 20–39 Observed water level time series n/a 001/031
     IS V   Special aeronautical observations (SPECI) SPECI 000/011
     IS W   Aviation routine weather observations (mETAR) mETAR 000/010
     IS X   Other surface data IAC, IAC FLEET
  For T1T2 = 'IU'  then A1:
     IU A   Single level aircraft reports (automatic) AmDAR 004/000
     IU A   Single level aircraft reports (manual) AIREP/PIREP 004/001
     IU B   Single level balloon reports n/a
     IU C   (used for single level satellite-derived SAREP/SATOB 005/000
             reports – see Note 3)
     IU D   Dropsonde/Dropwindsondes TEmP DROP 002/007
     IU E   Ozone vertical sounding n/a 008/001
     IU I   Dispersal and transport analysis n/a 009/000
     IU J 01–19 Upper wind from fixed land stations (entire PILOT (parts A, 002/001
            sounding) B, C, D)
     IU J 20–39 Upper wind from mobile land stations (entire PILOT mOBIL 002/003
            sounding) (parts A, B, C, D)
     IU J 40–59 Upper wind from marine stations (entire PILOT SHIP 002/002
           sounding) (parts A, B, C, D)
     IU K 01–19 Radio soundings from fixed land stations TEmP (parts A, B) 002/004
           (up to 100 hPa)
     IU K 20–39 Radio soundings from mobile land stations TEmP mOBIL 002/006
          (up to 100 hPa) (parts A, B)
     IU K 40–59 Radio soundings from marine stations TEmP SHIP (parts A, B) 002/005
           (up to 100 hPa)
     IU M   Model derived sondes
     IU N   Rocketsondes
     IU O   Profiles of aircraft observations in ascending/ AmDAR 002/020
            descending
     IU P   Profilers PILOT 002/010
     IU Q   RASS temperature profilers TEmP 002/011
     IU R   (used for radiance data – see Note 3)
     IU S   01–19 Radiosondes/pibal reports from fixed land TEmP (parts A, B, C, D) 002/004
             stations (entire sounding)
     IU S 20–39 Radio soundings from mobile land stations TEmP mOBIL (parts A, 002/006
             (entire sounding) B, C, D)
     IU S 40–59 Radio soundings from marine stations TEmP SHIP (parts A, 002/005
             (entire sounding) B, C, D)
     IU T   (used for satellite-derived sondes – see Note 3) SATEm, SARAD, SATOB
     IU U 01–45 Monthly statistics of data from upper-air stations CLImAT TEmP 002/025
     IU U 46–59 Monthly statistics of data from marine stations CLImAT TEmP, SHIP 002/026

     IO R   Sea surface observations TRACKOB 031/001
     IO S   Sea surface and below soundings BATHY, TESAC 031/005
     IO T   Sea surface temperature
     IO W   Sea surface waves WAVEOB 031/002
     IO X   Other sea environmental
  About A2
     A   0 - 90W northern hemisphere
     B   90W - 180 northern hemisphere
     C   180 - 90E northern hemisphere
     D   90E - 0 northern hemisphere
     E   0 - 90W tropical belt
     F   90W - 180 tropical belt
     G   180 - 90E tropical belt
     H   90E - 0 tropical belt
     I   0 - 90W southern hemisphere
     J   90W - 180 southern hemisphere
     K   180 - 90E southern hemisphere
     L   90E - 0 southern hemisphere
     M   Lower left 10S 100E/upper right 70N 110W
     N   Northern hemisphere
     P   Area between 64.69N - 136.76W, 55.61N - 13.43W
     64.69N - 156.76W, 55.61N - 33.43W
     S   Southern hemisphere
     T   45W - 180 northern hemisphere
     U   Area between 21.0N - 128.1W, 36.0N - 130.9W
               21.1N - 113.0W, 36.2N - 110.5W
     V   Area between 30.3N - 83.7W, 51.0N - 68.9W
               19.8N - 64.5W, 33.3N - 47.1W
     X   Global Area (area not definable)
 ICAO is the ICAO index for release center.
 YYGGgg is the nominal release time (day, hour, minute) UTC
 ORD is the order sequence as RRA, RRB, CCA .... is optional

)

parses a subset sequence as an Land fixed SYNOP FM-12, SHIP FM-13 or SYNOP-mobil FM-14 report

Parameters
mpointer to a struct metreport where set some results
spointer to a struct bufr2tac_subset_state
sqpointer to a struct bufr_subset_sequence_data with the parsed sequence on input
errstring with detected errors, if any

It return 0 if all is OK. Otherwise returns 1 and it also fills the err string

414  if ( d->flags & TEMP_POINT_MASK_STANDARD_LEVEL )
415  {
416  ix = ( int ) ( d->p * 0.01 + 0.5 ); // hPa
417  ix = ( ix / 10 ) % 100; // coded
418  if ( is_over_100 )
419  sprintf ( t->c.s2.std[isc].PnPn, "%02d", ix ); // PnPn
420  else
421  sprintf ( t->a.s2.std[isa].PnPn, "%02d", ix ); // PnPn
422 
423  ix = ( int ) ( d->h + 0.5 );
424  if ( d->p <= 50000.0 )
425  {
426  if ( is_over_100 )
427  sprintf ( t->c.s2.std[isc].hnhnhn, "%03d", ( ( ix + 5 ) / 10 ) % 1000 );
428  else
429  sprintf ( t->a.s2.std[isa].hnhnhn, "%03d", ( ( ix + 5 ) / 10 ) % 1000 );
430  }
431  else
432  {
433  if ( is_over_100 )
434  sprintf ( t->c.s2.std[isc].hnhnhn, "%03d", ix % 1000 );
435  else if ( ix >= 0 )
436  sprintf ( t->a.s2.std[isa].hnhnhn, "%03d", ix % 1000 );
437  else
438  sprintf ( t->a.s2.std[isa].hnhnhn, "%03d", ( -ix + 500 ) % 1000 );
439  }
440  if ( is_over_100 )
441  {
442  kelvin_to_TTTa ( t->c.s2.std[isc].TnTnTan, d->T ); // TnTnTan
443  dewpoint_depression_to_DnDn ( t->c.s2.std[isc].DnDn, d->T, d->Td ); // DnDn
444  wind_to_dndnfnfnfn ( t->c.s2.std[isc].dndnfnfnfn, d->dd, d->ff ); // dndnfnfnfn
445  // Now update Id
446  if ( d->ff != MISSING_REAL && d->dd != MISSING_REAL )
447  {
448  t->c.s1.id[0] = t->c.s2.std[isc].PnPn[0];
449  }
450  if ( isc < TEMP_NSTAND_MAX )
451  {
452  isc += 1;
453  t->c.s2.n = isc;
454  }
455  }
456  else
457  {
458  kelvin_to_TTTa ( t->a.s2.std[isa].TnTnTan, d->T ); // TnTnTan
459  dewpoint_depression_to_DnDn ( t->a.s2.std[isa].DnDn, d->T , d->Td ); // DnDn
460  wind_to_dndnfnfnfn ( t->a.s2.std[isa].dndnfnfnfn, d->dd, d->ff ); // dndnfnfnfn
461  // Now update Id
462  if ( d->ff != MISSING_REAL && d->dd != MISSING_REAL )
463  {
464  t->a.s1.id[0] = t->a.s2.std[isa].PnPn[0];
465  }
466  if ( isa < TEMP_NSTAND_MAX )
467  {
468  isa += 1;
469  t->a.s2.n = isa;
470  }
471  }
472  }
473 
474  // Tropopause level
475  if ( d->flags & TEMP_POINT_MASK_TROPOPAUSE_LEVEL )
476  {
477  if ( is_over_100 )
478  {
479  ix = ( int ) ( d->p * 0.1 + 0.5 );
480  sprintf ( t->c.s3.trop[itc].PnPnPn, "%03d", ix % 1000 ); // PnPnPn
481  kelvin_to_TTTa ( t->c.s3.trop[itc].TnTnTan, d->T ); // TnTnTan
482  dewpoint_depression_to_DnDn ( t->c.s3.trop[itc].DnDn, d->T , d->Td ); // DnDn
483  wind_to_dndnfnfnfn ( t->c.s3.trop[itc].dndnfnfnfn, d->dd, d->ff ); // dndnfnfnfn
484  if ( ix && itc < TEMP_NTROP_MAX )
485  {
486  itc += 1;
487  t->c.s3.n = itc;
488  }
489  }
490  else
491  {
492  ix = ( int ) ( d->p * 0.01 + 0.5 );
493  sprintf ( t->a.s3.trop[ita].PnPnPn, "%03d", ix % 1000 ); // PnPnPn.
494  kelvin_to_TTTa ( t->a.s3.trop[ita].TnTnTan, d->T ); // TnTnTan
495  dewpoint_depression_to_DnDn ( t->a.s3.trop[ita].DnDn, d->T , d->Td ); // DnDn
496  wind_to_dndnfnfnfn ( t->a.s3.trop[ita].dndnfnfnfn, d->dd, d->ff ); // dndnfnfnfn
497  if ( ix && ita < TEMP_NTROP_MAX )
498  {
499  ita += 1;
500  t->a.s3.n = ita;
501  }
502  }
503  }
504 
505  // Max wind level
506  if ( d->flags & TEMP_POINT_MASK_MAXIMUM_WIND_LEVEL )
507  {
508  if ( is_over_100 )
509  {
510  ix = ( int ) ( d->p * 0.1 + 0.5 );
511  sprintf ( t->c.s4.windx[iwxc].PmPmPm, "%03d", ix % 1000 ); // PnPnPn
512  wind_to_dndnfnfnfn ( t->c.s4.windx[iwxc].dmdmfmfmfm, d->dd, d->ff ); // dndnfnfnfn
513  // check if more wind data
514  for ( j = i + 1; j < r->n ; j++ )
515  {
516  if ( r->raw[j].ff != MISSING_REAL )
517  {
518  t->c.s4.windx[iwxc].no_last_wind = 1;
519  break;
520  }
521  }
522  if ( ix && iwxc < TEMP_NMAXWIND_MAX )
523  {
524  iwxc += 1;
525  t->c.s4.n = iwxc;
526  }
527  }
528  else
529  {
530  ix = ( int ) ( d->p * 0.01 + 0.5 );
531  sprintf ( t->a.s4.windx[iwxa].PmPmPm, "%03d", ix % 1000 ); // PnPnPn.
532  wind_to_dndnfnfnfn ( t->a.s4.windx[iwxa].dmdmfmfmfm, d->dd, d->ff ); // dndnfnfnfn
533  for ( j = i + 1; j < r->n ; j++ )
534  {
535  if ( r->raw[j].ff != MISSING_REAL )
536  {
537  t->a.s4.windx[iwxa].no_last_wind = 1;
538  break;
539  }
540  }
541  if ( ix && iwxa < TEMP_NMAXWIND_MAX )
542  {
543  iwxa += 1;
544  t->a.s4.n = iwxa;
545  }
546  }
547  }
548 
549  // Significant TH points
550  if ( d->flags & ( TEMP_POINT_MASK_SIGNIFICANT_TEMPERATURE_LEVEL | TEMP_POINT_MASK_SIGNIFICANT_HUMIDITY_LEVEL ) )
551  {
552  if ( is_over_100 )
553  {
554  sprintf ( t->d.s5.th[itd].nini, "%d%d", ( ( int ) itd - 1 ) %9 + 1, ( ( int ) itd - 1 ) %9 + 1 );
555  ix = ( int ) ( d->p * 0.1 + 0.5 );
556  sprintf ( t->d.s5.th[itd].PnPnPn, "%03d", ix ); // PnPnPn

559  if ( ix && itd < TEMP_NMAX_POINTS )
560  {
561  itd += 1;
562  t->d.s5.n = itd;
563  }
564  }
565  else
566  {
567  if ( d->flags & TEMP_POINT_MASK_SURFACE )
568  {
569  strcpy ( t->b.s5.th[itb].nini, "00" ); // case of surface level
570  }
571  else
572  {
573  sprintf ( t->b.s5.th[itb].nini, "%d%d", ( ( int ) itb - 1 ) %9 + 1, ( ( int ) itb - 1 ) %9 + 1 );

580  {
581  itb += 1;
582  t->b.s5.n = itb;
583  }
584  }
585  }
586 
587  // Significant wind points
588  if ( d->flags & TEMP_POINT_MASK_SIGNIFICANT_WIND_LEVEL )
589  {
590  if ( is_over_100 )

625  // Now we set some bit masks
626  if ( isa )

628  if ( isc )

549  // Because this is the first descriptor in a sequence for a point, we use this
550  // descriptor to set properly the current index
551  if ( s->rep > 0 )
552  {
553  // case of Temperature, humidty ... point
554  if ( ( int ) s->r->n < s->rep )
555  {
556  // Because of there are bufr reports with a lot of not significant points
557  // we only collect the first one and significant points, i.e. those that flags are non zero
558  // When flags are zero we just overwrite points
559  if ( s->r->n < ( RAW_TEMP_NMAX_POINTS ) &&
560  ( s->r->n == 0 || s->r->raw[s->r->n - 1].flags ) )
561  {
562  s->r->n += 1; // Here we update the index
563  }
564  }
565  s->r->raw[s->r->n - 1].dt = s->ival;
566  }
567  else
568  {
569  // case of wind shear point
570  if ( ( int ) s->w->n < s->itval )
571  {
572  s->w->n += 1;
573  }
574  s->w->raw[s->w->n - 1].dt = s->ival;
575  }
576  break;
577  default:
578  break;
579  }
580  return 0;
581 }
